chunks.html_content: If you’re self-employed and your profits are £12,570 or more a year, you usually pay Class 2 and Class 4 National Insurance rates.
chunks.plain_content:
Self-employed National Insurance rates
If you’re self-employed and your profits are £12,570 or more a year, you usually pay Class 2 and Class 4 National Insurance rates.

chunks.html_content: You work out your profits by deducting your expenses from your self-employed income.
chunks.plain_content:
Self-employed National Insurance rates
You work out your profits by deducting your expenses from your self-employed income.

chunks.html_content: Most people pay Class 2 and Class 4 National Insurance through Self Assessment.
chunks.plain_content:
Self-employed National Insurance rates
How to pay
Most people pay Class 2 and Class 4 National Insurance through Self Assessment.

chunks.html_content: You must tell HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) when you become self-employed as a sole trader or as a partnership.
chunks.plain_content:
Self-employed National Insurance rates
How to pay
You must tell HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) when you become self-employed as a sole trader or as a partnership.

chunks.html_content:
Some self-employed people do not pay National Insurance through Self Assessment, but may want to pay voluntary contributions. These are:

  • examiners, moderators, invigilators and people who set exam questions
  • people who run businesses involving land or property
  • ministers of religion who do not receive a salary or stipend
  • people who make investments for themselves or others - but not as a business and without getting a fee or commission
